  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Low risk — our terms ARE standard, just not Lau's standard",
    "content": "**Low risk, for one decisive reason: our terms are not non-standard. They are a different standard.**\n\n\"Humaneness\" for 仁 is Ames and Rosemont, Van Norden, and Slingerland. \"Rightness\" for 义 is Van Norden and Ivanhoe (in some works). \"Ritual conduct\" for 礼 is close to Slingerland's \"ritual\" and Ames's \"ritual propriety.\" No sinologist will see these and question the author's competence -- they will recognize a deliberate terminological choice from within the range of established scholarly options.\n\nThe real credibility risk runs the other direction: if we use Lau's \"benevolence\" in the quote and then switch to \"humaneness\" in the analysis, a careful reviewer will ask *why* the author uses different English words for the same character in the same passage. That looks like inconsistency or carelessness -- worse for credibility than a non-Lau rendering.\n\nA single TN suffices: \"Our translation of classical passages follows the terminological conventions of this volume. For standard alternative renderings, see Lau (1963) or Ivanhoe (2003).\" This signals competence (we know the alternatives exist) while justifying our choice (consistency with the author's framework).\n"
  }
}
